PROJECT OVERVIEW 
This project, titled the Digital Literacy Portfolio, is the primary deliverable for the CSE0001 
course. It is designed to demonstrate a student's proficiency in navigating the modern digital 
landscape. The project is hosted on GitHub, representing a transition from being a passive 
consumer of technology to an active, professional digital citizen. 
The portfolio is structured around five key pillars: 
1. Infographics). 
2. Professional Identity: Establishing a presence on industry-standard platforms like 
LinkedIn, GitHub, Kaggle, and Stack Overflow. 
3. Technical Collaboration: Engaging with coding platforms (HackerRank) and data 
collection tools (Google Forms). 
4. Effective Communication: Mastering professional email etiquette and responsible 
social media habits. 
5. Cyber Security: Researching real-world threats like UPI fraud to promote digital safety. 
The Scenario 
In this project, I am acting in the role of a Student Digital Ambassador. The scenario assumes 
that I have been selected by the university to lead and mentor my peers in the digital space. 
As an ambassador, my responsibility is not just to learn these tools for myself, but to build a 
repository of resources—such as a "Stay Safe Online" checklist and professional 
communication templates—that can help other students at VIT Bhopal University. This portfolio 
serves as my official "ambassador toolkit," which is presented to a faculty committee to prove 
that I can represent the university's digital standards and help protect the student body from 
common online risks. 
Task 1: Digital Literacy Awareness Infographic 
• What was made: I designed an original infographic titled "What is Digital Literacy?". 
The purpose of this visual guide is to educate my peers at VIT Bhopal on the essential 
components of being digitally literate. The infographic defines digital literacy, highlights 
essential tools for modern students (such as Canva for design and Zoom for 
collaboration), and provides a clear section on Safe Internet Practices, including 
recognizing phishing attempts and protecting personal data. 
• Tool used: I used Canva, a browser-based graphic design tool. This platform allowed 
me to use professional layouts and icons to make the information engaging and easy to 
read for a student audience. 
• Reflection: Creating this infographic helped me realize that digital literacy is not just 
about knowing how to use a computer, but about using technology critically and 
safely. The most challenging part was condensing a large amount of information into a 
single visual page without making it look cluttered. As a Student Digital Ambassador, I 
learned that visual communication is one of the most effective ways to spread 
awareness about cyber safety. This task has improved my ability to present technical 
information in a way that is accessible to everyone. 
Task 2: Student Digital Portfolio 
• Platforms Set Up: For this task, I established my professional digital presence across 
four major industry platforms: GitHub, LinkedIn, Kaggle, and Stack Overflow. I also 
created a "Profile README" on GitHub—a specialized repository that acts as a live 
landing page for my developer profile, featuring my branch, academic goals, and 
technical focus. 
• Purpose: As a Student Digital Ambassador, the purpose of setting up these specific 
platforms is to move beyond social networking and into professional branding. LinkedIn 
serves as my digital resume and a hub for networking with VIT alumni and industry 
leaders. GitHub and Kaggle allow me to showcase my actual "proof of work"—from 
Python scripts to data analysis projects—while Stack Overflow integrates me into the 
global developer community where I can learn through collaborative problem-solving. 
• Future Plans: Over the next four years of my B.Tech in Cloud Computing and 
Automation, I plan to use these platforms as a growing archive of my academic journey. 
I will use GitHub to document my progress in automation scripting and cloud 
infrastructure projects. On LinkedIn, I intend to share my certifications and course 
milestones to build a bridge toward summer internships. By maintaining these profiles 
now, I am ensuring that by the time I graduate in 2029, I have a verifiable and 
professional "Digital Footprint" that distinguishes me to recruiters in the competitive 
cloud technology sector. 
Task 3: Coding & Collaboration Platforms 
• Platforms Used: For this task, I utilized two essential cloud-based platforms: 
HackerRank and Google Forms. These tools represent two different but equally 
important sides of digital literacy—technical problem-solving and digital data 
collection/collaboration. 
• What I Practiced (HackerRank): I used HackerRank to practice and demonstrate my 
foundational programming skills. As a student specializing in Cloud Computing and 
Automation, technical proficiency is a core requirement. I successfully completed a 
problem-solving challenge on the platform, which tested my ability to write clean, 
logical code and pass specific test cases. This exercise allowed me to familiarize myself 
with competitive coding environments and automated grading systems that are widely 
used in the tech industry today. 
• What I Built (Google Forms): I designed and implemented a Digital Literacy 
Awareness Quiz using Google Forms. This quiz consists of five targeted questions—four 
multiple-choice questions focusing on digital security and LinkedIn professionalism, 
and one short-answer question regarding the importance of a professional digital 
footprint. By building this, I practiced how to create professional surveys, set up 
automated response sheets, and analyze data collected from a group. 
• Reflection: This task highlighted the importance of using the right tool for the right job. 
While HackerRank sharpened my logical thinking, Google Forms taught me how to 
facilitate digital outreach and collaboration. Both platforms are integral to my academic 
journey at VIT Bhopal, as they provide the infrastructure needed for both individual 
technical growth and team-based project management. 
Task 4: Professional Communication 
• Communication Scenario: In this task, I practiced formal digital communication by 
drafting two distinct professional emails and a social media etiquette guide. The first 
scenario involved writing to Dr. Sharma to request an assignment extension for the 
Digital Literacy course due to health issues. The second scenario involved a proactive 
inquiry to an Internship Coordinator expressing interest in a summer internship, 
highlighting my specialization in Cloud Computing and Automation and my 
foundational skills in Python. Additionally, I developed a comprehensive "Do’s and 
Don’ts" checklist for social media use, focusing on privacy, professional branding, and 
respectful interaction. 
• Key Learnings: 1. The Power of Structure: I learned that a professional email must 
contain a clear, descriptive subject line, a formal greeting, a concise body, and a proper 
sign-off. As seen in my drafts, including my registration number and branch helps the 
recipient identify me immediately. 2. Digital Reputation: Developing the social media 
checklist taught me that as a student, my "Digital Footprint" is a permanent resume. 
Avoiding offensive content and oversharing personal details is crucial for maintaining a 
professional image for future recruiters. 3. Clarity and Tone: I realized that being direct 
yet polite is essential. For instance, in the extension request, providing a specific new 
deadline (07/04/26) shows accountability and respect for the professor's schedule. 4. 
Consequences of Poor Communication: Through this task, I understood that informal 
or poorly structured communication can lead to missed opportunities, such as an 
internship inquiry being marked as spam or a professor denying a valid request due to a 
lack of professional tone. 
Task 5: Cybercrime Awareness 
• Case Study Findings: For this module, I analyzed UPI Payment Fraud, specifically 
focusing on the "Request Money" scam. My research highlighted how attackers use 
"Collect Requests" on apps like GPay or PhonePe to trick people into authorizing a 
transaction that actually debits their account. The most important lesson from this 
study is that many victims lose money simply because they don't realize a UPI PIN is 
only required to send money, never to receive it. This type of fraud doesn't just cause 
financial damage; it leads to a significant loss of trust in the digital systems we use every 
day. 
• One Habit I Am Changing: After creating my "Stay Safe Online" checklist, I’ve decided 
to adopt a much stricter "Verify Before Action" approach. I will no longer scan QR 
codes or click on shortened links sent by unknown individuals on WhatsApp or 
marketplace platforms. More importantly, as a student in Cloud Computing and 
Automation, I have now made it a mandatory habit to enable Two-Factor 
Authentication (2FA) across all my professional and academic accounts, including 
GitHub and LinkedIn. I’ve realized that digital safety is a personal responsibility, and I 
will never enter my PIN unless I am the one intentionally initiating a payment. 
Conclusion: Overall Learning 
Completing this Digital Literacy project has been a transformative experience that bridged the 
gap between being a student and becoming a professional in the tech industry. As a first-year 
student specializing in Cloud Computing and Automation, I initially viewed digital literacy as 
simply knowing how to use software. However, through the five tasks of this portfolio, I have 
learned that true digital literacy is about building a secure, professional, and impactful digital 
identity. 
Key Takeaways: 
• Professional Branding: Setting up my GitHub, LinkedIn, and Kaggle profiles taught me 
that my digital footprint is my permanent resume. I now understand how to showcase 
my "proof of work" to future recruiters. 
• Effective Advocacy: In my role as a Student Digital Ambassador, I learned that 
simplifying complex information—whether through infographics or safety checklists—is 
a vital skill for leadership. 
• Cyber Resilience: My research into UPI "Collect Request" fraud was a major turning 
point. It highlighted that technical knowledge must be paired with constant vigilance. 
Learning that a PIN is never needed to receive money is a lesson I will continue to share 
with my peers. 
• Technical Communication: Drafting formal emails and collaboration tools like Google 
Forms helped me master the "soft skills" that are just as important as coding in the 
engineering world. 
In summary, this project has equipped me with the foundational tools to navigate the cloud 
industry safely and professionally. I am now more confident in my ability to use technology 
responsibly, collaborate with others effectively, and protect myself and my community from 
digital threats. 
 
